  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "What are the penalties for money laundering under federal law?",
  "response": "Under federal law in the United States, money laundering is a serious offense with significant penalties. The penalties can vary based on the specific circumstances of the case, including the amount of money involved, the nature of the underlying criminal activity, and whether the defendant has a prior criminal history. Here are the key penalties for money laundering under federal law:\n\n### **Criminal Penalties**\n1. **Imprisonment**: \n   - Individuals convicted of money laundering can face up to **20 years in federal prison** for each violation.\n   - If the money laundering is connected to a violation of certain other federal laws (e.g., terrorism financing), the maximum prison term can be **up to 30 years**.\n\n2. **Fines**:\n   - The maximum fine for money laundering is **$500,000 or twice the value of the laundered funds, whichever is greater**.\n   - For organizations (e.g., businesses), the fine can be up to **$1 million or twice the value of the laundered funds, whichever is greater**.\n\n3. **Asset Forfeiture**:\n   - The government may seize and forfeit any property or funds involved in or obtained through money laundering activities.\n\n4. **Enhanced Penalties for Certain Cases**:\n   - If the underlying criminal activity involves **narcotics trafficking**, additional penalties may apply, including **mandatory minimum sentences**.\n   - Money laundering related to **terrorism** can result in enhanced penalties, including longer prison terms.\n\n### **Civil Penalties**\nIn addition to criminal penalties, individuals and organizations may face civil penalties for money laundering, including:\n   - Fines up to **$10,000 or the value of the laundered funds, whichever is greater**.\n   - **Forfeiture of assets** involved in the violation.\n\n### **Key Federal Statutes**\nMoney laundering offenses are primarily prosecuted under:\n   - **18 U.S.C. \u00a7 1956**: Prohibits conducting financial transactions involving proceeds from unlawful activities with the intent to promote illegal activity, conceal the source of funds, or evade taxes.\n   - **18 U.S.C. \u00a7 1957**: Prohibits engaging in monetary transactions involving criminally derived property valued at over $10,000.\n\n### **Other Consequences**\nBeyond criminal and civil penalties, individuals convicted of money laundering may face:\n   - Loss of professional licenses.\n   - Difficulty obtaining employment, especially in regulated industries like finance.\n   - Immigration consequences for non-U.S. citizens, including deportation or inadmissibility.\n\nIf you are facing allegations of money laundering, it is critical to consult with an experienced criminal defense attorney to understand your rights and legal options.",
  "temperature": 1.0,
